<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-284-224  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 284 224.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 20 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canada: Apple gets injunction in grey-market case.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Canada Inc. (cases)Megasoft Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     Computer industryCourt CasesLegal IssuesCopyrightCanadaTrademark.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CANADA: APPLE GETS INJUNCTION IN GREY-MARKET CASE MARKHAM, ONTARIO, CANADA,1990 MAR 14 (NB) -- Apple Canada has obtained an injunction preventingMegasoft, a Toronto computer dealer, from using Apple trademarks.andM;Apple filed suit against Megasoft in February and charged the dealer withinfringing on Apple trademarks, passing off non- Apple products as Appleproducts, and masquerading as an authorized Apple dealer.andM;The injunction, granted by the Federal Court of Canada, prohibits Megasoftand its owner, Jacob Fine, from representing company as an Apple dealer, andfrom using or displaying Apple trademarks or marks likely to be confused withApple trademarks.andP;  It also stops Megasoft from acquiring Apple products fromauthorized dealers, and from passing off non-Apple products as Appleproducts.andP;  Megasoft must also post notices on its premises, and includenotices in advertising and on invoices, stating it is not an Apple dealer.andM;Murray Vince, assistant legal counsel for Apple Canada, said Megasoft hasdisplayed logos closely resembling Apple trademarks, such as arainbow-striped Apple with a bite out of its left side (Apple's trademark hasthe bite on the right).andP;  &quot;They were at least creating the impression in theminds of consumers that they were an authorized dealer,&quot; he said.andM;Earlier, Fine told Newsbytes Apple's allegations were &quot;completely withoutfoundation and have no basis in truth or fact.&quot;andM;(Grant Buckler/19900316/Press Contact: Murray Vince or Norm Kirkpatrick,Apple Canada, 416-477-5800; Jacob Fine, MegaSoft, 416-785-8887)</TEXT></DOC>